    <statement><div><p>During a simulation, a machine amplifies a signal using exponential growth. After several cycles, the signal reaches a strength of <m>{64}</m>, 
generated using base <m>{4}</m>.</p>
<p>Write the logarithmic form of the statement:</p>

<p><me>
{4}^{3} = {64}
</me></p>

<p>Express your answer in the form <m>\log_{a}(b)</m>.</p>

<p><fillin characters="15" name="ans1"/>  </p></div></statement>
    <solution><div><h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>The exponential relationship is:</p>

<p><me>
{4}^{3} = {64}.
</me></p>

<p>We use the identity:</p>

<p><me>
a^k = N \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad \log_a(N) = k.
</me></p>

<p>So:</p>

<p><me>
\log_{ {4} }({64}) = {3}.
</me></p>

<p>This is written as:</p>

<p><me>
\frac{\log({64})}{\log({4})}.
</me></p></div></solution>
    <answer><p><m>\frac{\ln \left( 64 \right)}{\ln \left( 4 \right)}</m></p></answer>
